Basic EDA and Data Generating Process :

For our time series analysis , we are considering 12 years of data from 2010 to 2022.The plot shows the trend of global temperature anomalies. from January 2010 to December 2022.

Code 
data_monthly %>%

  xlab("Year") +

Facebook Prophet Model :

A facebook prophet model decomposes the time series data into multiple components : trend, seasonality and holidays. The trend component helps us understand the magnitude of change over time.The seasonality component helps us understand repeating patterns over fixed intervals , in our case it is yearly. Because the data we are considering is global temperature anomalies data , special events should not have a drastic impact on it.The trend is modeled using a Bayesian structural time-series model that considers historical trends and seasonality, including changepoints. This approach allows for flexible modeling of seasonal patterns and any irregular patterns in the data.

Code 
prophet_data = data_monthly %>% 
    rename(ds = Year, # Have to name our date variable "ds"
    y = Value)  # Have to name our time series "y"

train = prophet_data %>%  # Train set
  filter(ds<ymd("2022-01-01"))

test = prophet_data %>% # Test set
  filter(ds>=ymd("2022-01-01"))

orig_model = prophet(train) # Train Model

orig_future = make_future_dataframe(orig_model,periods = 12,freq='month') 

orig_forecast = predict(orig_model,orig_future) # Get forecast

plot(orig_model,orig_forecast)+
  ylab("Temp Anomalies")+
  xlab("Year")+
  theme_bw()+
  ggtitle("Prophet Model Forecast")

Original Model : 25 Changepoints

Change points for initial model or original model. For the original model which has 25 change points , we notice that the change points are accumulated right after the year 2015, which resonates with the trend in the data which shows a substantial spike after 2015, this is because in the latter half of 2015 and 2016, the El Nino event had a direct impact on the increase in global earth temperature which caused the highest temperature fluctuation ever recorded but it does not accurately capture all the trends in our data.

Code 
plot(orig_model,orig_forecast) +
  add_changepoints_to_plot(orig_model) +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Temperture Anomalies")

We are well aware that increasing or decreasing the number of changepoints in our data will result in overfitting or underfitting and might throw our bias and variance off guard, to avoid this we need to carefully consider the number of changepoints in a way that it captures the trend in our time series data and does not overfit or underfit at the same time. This is done so that forecasting is more accurate and provides insights into the underlying dynamics of our data because we identify the points where the trend or level of our data changes and then model it as per that.

New Model with 20 Change Points :

When compared to our original model when we consider only 20 change points , I believe it helps us determine the underlying trend in a better manner.If we notice the original plot of our data, there are substantial dips after 2010 which was not captured before but we both our models do not account for the fluctuation around 2020, this might be because our prophet model is not sensitive to out.Nevertheless, to confirm this we will compare the RMSE values for these model at a later stage.

Code 
# Number of Changepoints

#model = prophet(train,n.changepoints=10, changepoint.range = 0.9)
model1 = prophet(train,n.changepoints=15, changepoint.range = 1, changepoint.prior.scale = 0.1)


forecast1 = predict(model1,orig_future)

plot(model1,forecast1)+add_changepoints_to_plot(model1)+ylim(0.2,1.5)+theme_bw()+xlab("Year")+ylab("Temperature Anomalies")

The trend line below shows us the increasing temperatures globally with a peak in and around the year 2015 which resonates with our time series data. The increasing curve with slight dips indicates the trend.The decomposition of the model also confirms the presence of yearly seasonality in our data.

Code 
prophet_plot_components(model1, forecast1)

Comparison of linear growth vs logistic growth : MAPE,MAE and RMSE are measures of the difference between the predicted values and the actual values, and lower values indicate that the model is better at predicting the outcome of interest.In our scenario linear model has lower values in all three cases and therefore we do not require saturation maximums and minimums and we assume that linear model fits our data better.

Two Year forecast :

The data set in our hand is that of global temperature anomalies , we can never know or predict how much our temperature changes can vary by because it depends on external factors that mortal beings have little to no control over.For this reason, I believe specifying saturating minimum and maximum points for this data set will not be necessary.

This can also be used to determine that our growth is linear and not logistic because we are not including saturation minimum or maximum in our data.

Code 
two_yr_future = make_future_dataframe(orig_model,periods = 24,freq='months')
two_yr_forecast = predict(orig_model,two_yr_future)

Code

Comparing additive and multiplicative Seasonality :

From the below RMSE values and plots , we can conclude that either of the seasonality works but the difference in RMSE values is negligible ,therefore we prefer additive seasonality over multiplicative.

Since we donât have daily data, we do not have any impact due to holidays.

Code 
mod1 = prophet(train,seasonality.mode='additive')
forecast1 = predict(mod1)

mod2 = prophet(train,seasonality.mode='multiplicative')
forecast2 = predict(mod2)

forecast_metric_data_add = forecast1 %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  mutate(ds = as.Date(ds))

RMSE = sqrt(mean((test$y - forecast_metric_data_add$yhat)^2))

print(paste("RMSE for additive seasonality:",round(RMSE,2)))
[1] "RMSE for additive seasonality: 0.13"
Code 
forecast_metric_data_multi = forecast2 %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  mutate(ds = as.Date(ds))

RMSE = sqrt(mean((test$y - forecast_metric_data_multi$yhat)^2))

print(paste("RMSE for multiplicative seasonality:",round(RMSE,2)))
[1] "RMSE for multiplicative seasonality: 0.12"
Code 
additive = prophet(train)
add_fcst = predict(additive,orig_future)

ylim(0.2,1.5)

6 month Prophet Forecast :

The 6 month forecast looks good as it does capture the underlying trend in our data.

Code 
best_fit_model = prophet::prophet(train,growth = 'linear', seasonality.mode = 'additive', n.changepoints=20, changepoint.range = 1, changepoint.prior.scale = 0.1) # Train Model
best_fit_future = make_future_dataframe(best_fit_model,periods = 6, freq= 'months') # Create future dataframe for predictions

best_fit_forecast = predict(best_fit_model,best_fit_future) # Get forecast

ggplot()+
geom_line(aes(as.Date(train$ds),train$y), size = 0.3)+
geom_line(aes(as.Date(best_fit_forecast$ds),best_fit_forecast$yhat),color='blue', alpha = 0.6)+
theme_bw()+
ylab('Temperature Anomalies')+
xlab('Year')+
ggtitle("Actual vs Predicted (blue) for 6 month forecast")
